<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-695-552  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 695 552.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  July 23 1990 v7 n28 p9(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Text retrieval system combs through data, can overlap text fields.andO;(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bowen, Ted Smalley.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Open Text Systems Inc's PAT ASCII text editor software is an ASCIItext retrieval system that can sift through overlapping textfields.andP;  The program is written in C and has been ported to VMSand Unix systems, including Ultrix and Xenix.andP;  The new system cansearch an entire data base or a specified sub-region, which can bedefined at run time and can nest and overlap in unrestrictedcombinations.andP;  The new text editor supports index points for eachcharacter in the database and can conduct proximity.andP;  PAT ASCIIcomes with Lector and the Transduction Toolkit and is availablefrom $10,000 to $40,000 per module depending on CPU.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Open Text Systems Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   PAT ASCII (Search software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionASCIIC Programming LanguageInformation Storage and RetrievalSoftware PackagesText Editors.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Tektronix revamps its line of color X windows terminalsandM;PORTLAND, Ore.andP;  -- Tektronix has unveiled a family of X windows terminalswith a radically different look and a price/performance ratio that mightworry competing vendors.andM;The TekXpress X Station products consist of a desktop monitor connected to aredesigned CPU enclosure that sits upright on the desk or floor.andP;  The compactCPU module is about the size of a cereal box and packs a Motorola 68030microprocessor and a Texas Instruments 34020 graphics co-processor.andM;The 7-inch-wide, 10-inch-tall module is convection-cooled, providing quieter,more reliable performance, company officials claim.andP;  Tektronix backs itsclaim with a three-year product warranty.andM;Except for the low-end XP23 model, all TekXpress models boast color displaysand Tektronix's color matching system (CMS).andP;  CMS helps ensure that onscreencolors are matched exactly by printers and peripherals.andM;Eileen O'Brien, a terminals analyst with International Data Corp., a marketresearch company in Framingham, Mass., said the Tektronix CMS is an importantfeature for certain applications, such as color desktop publishing andconsumer product design.andP;  The significance of CMS will grow if Tektronixengineers are successful in their bid to have CMS established as an industrystandard by the MIT X Consortium, she said.andM;The combination of 68030-based performance, progressive ergonomic design andan extensive warranty may help Tektronix's TekXpress gain ground onmarket-leading Network Computing Devices of Mountain View, Calif., saidStephen Auditore, a consultant with the X Business Group, a market researchcompany in Fremont, Calif.andM;At the low end of the TekXpress product line, the XP23 is available with a19-inch, 1,280-line-by-1,024-pixel monochrome monitor for $3,495.andP;  Priced at$3,995, the XP25 replaces the monochrome display with a 14-inch,1,152-line-by-900-pixel color monitor.andP;  At $4,995, the XP27 features a19-inch color display with a resolution of 1,152 lines by 900 pixels.andP;  At thehigh end, the $5,996 XP29 offers a 19-inch color display with a resolution of1,280 lines by 1,024 pixels.andM;All models include 3MB of memory, expandable to 13MB.andP;  The products will beavailable this month.andM;A Tektronix spokesman said DECnet support for TekXpress machines is scheduledfor the end of the third quarter.andP;  Support for the Local Area Transportprotocol will follow shortly after the DECnet release, he said.andM;Tektronix Inc. is located at P.O. Box 14689, Portland OR 97215, (800)225-5434.andO;</TEXT></DOC>